http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/People%E2%80%99s-marches-to-converge-at-Mangaluru/article13998575.ece

The people’s marches that set off from seven locations in the State will converge in Mangaluru on January 30 to celebrate Mahatma Gandhi’s 68th death anniversary with a national conference titled ‘Sea of Coexistence’. The Karnataka Communal Harmony Forum (KCHF) will organise the event.Addressing a media conference here on Wednesday, Robin Christopher, KCHF State general secretary, said that the seven people’s marches that were named after different rivers would begin from seven iconic places of the State that had historically been demonstrating secular traditions and peaceful coexistence.“Netravathi-Malaprabha march begins from Kudalasangama in Bagalkote district, Sharavathi march from Shishunala in Gadag district, Sita-Bhadra march from Bababudangiri in Chikkamagaluru, Shambhavi-Cauvery march from Srirangapatna in Mandya district, Souparnika-Shalmala from Ankola in Uttara Kannada district, Kumaradhara-Phalgune march from Kaivara Tatayya Kshetra in Chikkaballapur and Kali-Krishna march from Tinthini Mouneshwara Kshetra in Yadgir district and converge in Mangaluru on January 30,” Mr. Christopher said.Swaraj Abhiyan leader Yogendra Yadav from New Delhi, human rights activist Teesta Setalvad from Mumbai, well-known writers Baraguru Ramachandrappa and Chandrashekhar Patil from Karnataka, will participate in the event.Yakshagana, drama, musical presentations of sufi, vachana, songs of struggles and daff qawwali would be major attractions of the day-long event.Around 10,000 people are expected to participate in the event,” Mr. Christopher said. KCHF leaders M.R. Bheri, Sharanappa Ballatagi and Shrinivas Kalavaladoddi, activist advocate N. Padmavardhan, and HKDSS leader Ramanjaneyalau were present.